# Multi-Agent Etiquette

Multiple agent sessions (Claude Code, Cursor, Codex) and humans can land commits on the same branch during a single sitting. Two failure modes have happened repeatedly:

1. **Commit absorption.** A sibling agent's broad `git add -A` scoops up another agent's staged-or-unstaged files. The substantive code lands, but commit message and attribution are wrong.
2. **Rogue reverts.** An agent sees an unfamiliar commit, assumes it is out of scope, and reverts intentional work from a parallel session.

The rules below prevent both.

## Rules

### 1. Work in a worktree when other agents may be active

The integration tree is shared. Long batches do not belong there. Create an isolated git worktree before starting non-trivial work. Most projects expose a setup recipe (`just setup worktree-new <branch>`, `gh workspace`, etc.) that bootstraps a worktree with dependencies installed. If not, fall back to:

```bash
git worktree add -b <branch> .worktrees/<branch> HEAD
```

### 2. Commit per logical batch, never at end of session

After each batch of edits, stage only the files you touched and commit immediately. Do not pile up a multi-batch sweep and commit at the end. A sibling agent's `git add -A` will scoop up your pending work between batches.

### 3. Stage only files you authored

Never `git add -A` or `git add .` in a shared integration worktree. List the paths you touched and pass them explicitly. In a private worktree, broad globs are fine because no sibling agent shares the working tree.

**Lockfile corollary.** When you edit a manifest (`Cargo.toml`, `pyproject.toml`, `package.json`, etc.), also stage the matching lockfile (`Cargo.lock`, `uv.lock`, `pnpm-lock.yaml`) in the same commit. Path-scoped staging routinely orphans these; lockfile drift has happened more than once. If your manifest change touched a lockfile, the lockfile is one of "the paths you touched."

### 4. Coexist with unfamiliar uncommitted files

Before `git add`, run `git status` and note files you did not author. Do not pass judgement on them. Leave them in place, stage only your own paths, and commit. The default is peaceful coexistence: if there is no merge conflict and no hook failure on a file you must touch, just keep working.

Surface unfamiliar files to the user only when they actually block your commit. The user will then tell you whether to absorb them into your commit or ignore them — that decision is theirs, not yours.

### 5. Do not modify another agent's files

Read-only is fine; edits are not. If a pre-commit hook fails on a file you did not author, do not "fix" it. Mention the failure in passing and keep working on your own changes. Work from parallel sessions is intentional even when it looks out of scope from your task's perspective.

### 6. End every session with an explicit worktree-safe-to-close verdict

Before signing off, state plainly one of:

- **"Worktree safe to remove"** — everything is committed and pushed or merged, nothing left to do.
- **"Worktree NOT safe to remove"** — with a one-line reason (uncommitted edits, unpushed commits, follow-ups still in flight, etc.).

Do not remove the worktree yourself. The user manages cleanup, but they should not have to ask whether it is safe. The verdict is non-optional, even on tiny doc-only sessions, and even if you think it is obvious. Run `git status` and `git log @{u}..` (or equivalent) to verify before stating the verdict.

### 7. Never force-remove a worktree without three checks

If you ever do remove a worktree (e.g. user explicitly asks, or you are running a cleanup skill), run all three of these checks first and stop if ANY shows activity:

1. **Active agent session?**
   ```bash
   # Claude Code: sessions live under ~/.claude/projects/<encoded-cwd>/
   ls -la ~/.claude/projects/$(pwd | sed 's|/|-|g')*/
   ```
   The path is the worktree path with `/` replaced by `-`. If a `*.jsonl` is there with an mtime in the last few hours, a session is live. Killing the worktree leaves the session's CWD pointing at a deleted directory.

2. **Commits ahead of main?**
   ```bash
   git log --oneline main..<branch>
   ```
   `[gone]` after a squash-merge means the FIRST commit was merged via PR. Subsequent commits piled on top of the branch are NOT merged and exist only via the branch ref. Cross-check each "ahead" commit against `git log --all --oneline --grep="<subject>"` before agreeing it is safe.

3. **Uncommitted/untracked work in the worktree.**
   `git -C <path> status --short`. Any output combined with a recent worktree mtime is a strong signal of live work, not orphan litter to be preserved.

The `[gone]` remote status is the WEAKEST of the available signals about what is actually in the worktree. Treat any cleanup-skill candidate list as exactly that — a candidate set, never an authorization. Surface findings to the user with the session id and ahead commits, and let them decide.

The `--force` flag on `git worktree remove` is irreversible. Never use it without explicit user confirmation. When `git worktree remove` fails on modified/untracked files, report what is in the worktree and ask the user before bypassing the warning.

### 8. Back up before destructive history rewrites

Before `git filter-repo`, `git filter-branch`, BFG, or any tool that rewrites history, copy any affected files to a safe location first. `filter-repo` deletes target files from the working tree, not just from history. Past incidents: near-loss of `.env` files (with real API keys) because filter-repo removed them from both history and disk; only recovered because the remote had not been force-pushed yet.

Pattern: `cp <file> <file>.bak` before the operation, then remove the backup after confirming recovery.

### 9. Skip PRs for worktree merges when the project allows it

Some projects (single-developer, agent-heavy) merge worktree branches directly to `main` instead of opening PRs. Worktrees exist to prevent agent collisions, not to gate code review. Honour the project's policy — check the README / AGENTS.md / CONTRIBUTING for the convention before defaulting to either.

You cannot `git checkout main` inside a worktree, so the merge happens from the integration tree. Push the branch first, then `cd` to the main worktree and merge.

